data.title: Help! I don’t know how to wear make-up (aged 34)

data.text:
Not owning an iron. Guzzling pasta without guilt. Ignoring mountains of dust. I put these things down to being raised by my father — and I’m grateful to be relaxed about crumpled clothes, complex carbohydrates and cleaning regimes. However, a more irritating trait that, rightly or wrongly, I attribute to growing up as an only child in a woman-free home is my utter uselessness with make-up. Don’t wear it, can’t wear it.

My mother left when I was four — another story for another time — before I could rootle through her make-up bag, plaster expensive lipstick across my mouth or study her applying lotions and potions, powders and rouge. (Instead I remember lying in the bath as a young child while my dad shaved
